Luminal B. This subtype responds well to hormonal therapy (tamoxifen/aromatase inhibitors).
📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.34', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Breast', 'What is the most important contraindication for breast-conserving surgery?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Multicentric disease (cancer in multiple quadrants) is an absolute contraindication for BCS.
Other contraindications: previous chest wall RT, pregnancy, large tumour:breast ratio,
inflammatory breast cancer. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.53', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Breast', 'Which histological type of breast cancer is associated with loss of E-cadherin?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'ILC shows loss of E-cadherin (cell adhesion molecule), leading to diffuse infiltrative pattern
(Indian file pattern). It is the 2nd MC type, tends to be bilateral, and may be missed on
mammography due to its infiltrative nature. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.34', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Breast', 'Sentinel lymph node biopsy is performed using:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Dual technique (blue dye + Tc99m radiocolloid) gives the highest detection rate (>95%).
The sentinel node is the first node to receive lymphatic drainage from the tumour.
If negative on frozen section/H&E, axillary clearance is avoided. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.53', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Breast', 'Paget''s disease of the nipple is associated with:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Paget''s disease presents as eczematous changes of the nipple and ALWAYS has underlying
DCIS (with or without invasive component). Paget cells (large, clear, PAS-positive) are
found in nipple epidermis. Treatment involves mastectomy or central excision + RT. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.34', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Colorectal', 'What is the most common cause of small bowel obstruction in a patient with prior abdominal surgery?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Post-operative adhesions account for ~60% of SBO cases in patients with prior surgery.
In patients without prior surgery, hernias are the most common cause. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.71', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Colorectal', 'A 70-year-old presents with progressive abdominal distension, absolute constipation for 5 days, and late-onset vomiting. X-ray shows peripherally placed dilated bowel loops with haustral markings. What is the most likely diagnosis?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Peripherally placed dilated loops with haustra that don''t cross the entire lumen are characteristic
of LBO. Late vomiting and marked distension also favor large bowel pathology. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.49', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Colorectal', 'Rigler''s triad (pneumobilia + SBO + ectopic gallstone) is diagnostic of?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Gallstone ileus occurs when a large gallstone erodes through a cholecystoduodenal fistula and
impacts at the ileocaecal junction. Rigler''s triad on X-ray is pathognomonic. Bouveret syndrome
is gastric outlet obstruction by gallstone. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.71', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Colorectal', 'What is the investigation of choice to identify the site, cause, and complications of intestinal obstruction?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'CT abdomen is the gold standard — identifies transition point, cause of obstruction,
and signs of strangulation (bowel wall thickening, mesenteric haziness, pneumatosis).
📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.49', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Colorectal', 'A patient with sigmoid volvulus is hemodynamically stable with no signs of peritonitis. What is the initial management?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Uncomplicated sigmoid volvulus is initially managed with endoscopic decompression using a flatus tube
(success rate ~80%). This is followed by elective sigmoidectomy to prevent recurrence (60% recurrence
without surgery). Emergency surgery if signs of gangrene/perforation. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.71', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Colorectal', 'A 60-year-old male presents with iron-deficiency anemia and a palpable mass in the right iliac fossa. Colonoscopy shows a fungating mass in the caecum. What is the appropriate surgery?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Right hemicolectomy is the procedure for caecal and ascending colon cancers. It involves
resection from terminal ileum to proximal transverse colon with ligation of ileocolic,
right colic, and right branch of middle colic vessels. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.73', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Colorectal', 'Which gene mutation initiates the adenoma-carcinoma sequence?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'The APC (adenomatous polyposis coli) gene mutation on chromosome 5q21 is the initiating event
in the adenoma-carcinoma sequence (Vogelstein model). Loss of APC is also the germline mutation
in FAP. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.52', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Colorectal', 'A rectal cancer located 3 cm from the anal verge. What is the standard surgical procedure?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Tumours within 5 cm of the anal verge where sphincter preservation is not possible require
APR (Miles'' operation) with permanent end colostomy. For tumours >5 cm from verge, anterior
resection with TME is preferred. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.73', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Colorectal', 'The tumour marker used for monitoring recurrence of colorectal cancer is:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'CEA (carcinoembryonic antigen) is used for post-operative surveillance. Rising CEA suggests
recurrence. It is NOT used for screening (poor sensitivity/specificity). Baseline level has
prognostic significance. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.52', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Colorectal', 'Lynch syndrome (HNPCC) is caused by mutations in:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'HNPCC/Lynch syndrome results from germline mutations in DNA mismatch repair genes (MLH1, MSH2,
MSH6, PMS2) leading to microsatellite instability. It is the MC hereditary colorectal cancer
syndrome. Amsterdam II criteria used for clinical diagnosis. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.52', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Endocrine', 'A 25-year-old female has a thyroid nodule. FNAC shows Orphan Annie eye nuclei with psammoma bodies. What is the diagnosis?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Orphan Annie eye nuclei (clear, ground-glass), psammoma bodies, nuclear grooves, and
intranuclear inclusions are pathognomonic of papillary thyroid carcinoma. It is the MC
thyroid cancer with best prognosis. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.50', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Endocrine', 'Which thyroid cancer is associated with MEN 2A syndrome?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Medullary thyroid cancer (from C cells) is the thyroid component of MEN 2A (medullary ca +
pheochromocytoma + parathyroid hyperplasia) and MEN 2B (medullary ca + pheochromocytoma +
marfanoid habitus + mucosal neuromas). RET proto-oncogene mutation. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.37', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Endocrine', 'FNAC of a thyroid nodule shows Bethesda category IV (follicular neoplasm). What is the next step?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Bethesda IV (follicular neoplasm) has 15-30% malignancy risk. FNAC cannot differentiate
follicular adenoma from carcinoma (needs capsular/vascular invasion on histology).
Hemithyroidectomy provides tissue for definitive histological diagnosis. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.37', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Endocrine', 'After total thyroidectomy, a patient develops numbness and tingling in hands with carpopedal spasm. What is the cause?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Post-thyroidectomy hypocalcemia due to hypoparathyroidism presents with perioral/extremity
numbness, Chvostek''s sign, Trousseau''s sign (carpopedal spasm). Treatment: IV calcium
gluconate (acute), oral calcium + vitamin D (long-term). 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.50', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Endocrine', 'Which thyroid cancer does NOT take up radioactive iodine?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Medullary thyroid cancer arises from parafollicular C cells (not follicular cells),
hence does NOT concentrate iodine. RAI is ineffective. Treatment is surgical —
total thyroidectomy with central neck dissection. Calcitonin is the tumour marker. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.37', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'General Topics', 'A 70 kg man has 40% TBSA burns. Using the Parkland formula, what is the total fluid requirement in the first 24 hours?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Parkland formula: 4 × 70 × 40 = 11,200 mL of Ringer''s lactate in 24 hours.
Half (5600 mL) in the first 8 hours from time of burn, remaining 5600 mL over next 16 hours.
📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.20', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'General Topics', 'The most accurate method for TBSA assessment in children is:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Lund-Browder chart adjusts body surface area proportions for age (children have proportionally
larger heads). It is the most accurate method for all ages but especially important in pediatric burns.
📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.30', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'General Topics', 'Marjolin''s ulcer is:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Marjolin''s ulcer is an aggressive SCC arising in a chronic burn scar or non-healing wound
after a latent period of 10-25 years. It has a higher metastatic potential than regular SCC
and requires wide excision. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.30', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'General Topics', 'The best indicator of adequate fluid resuscitation in a burns patient is:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Urine output is the single best indicator of end-organ perfusion and fluid resuscitation adequacy.
Target: 0.5-1 mL/kg/hr in adults, 1-2 mL/kg/hr in children. More reliable than BP or HR
in burns patients. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.20', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'General Topics', 'Which organism is the most common cause of burn wound sepsis?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Pseudomonas aeruginosa is the MC organism causing burn wound sepsis. It produces a characteristic
blue-green exudate and fruity odor. Early wound excision and grafting reduces infection risk.
Initially Staph aureus colonizes, but Pseudomonas predominates by day 5-7. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.30', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'General Topics', 'A patient with pyloric stenosis presents with persistent vomiting. What is the expected acid-base disturbance?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Pyloric stenosis causes loss of gastric HCl → hypochloremia + metabolic alkalosis.
Associated hypokalemia (renal K+ loss) and paradoxical aciduria (kidney excretes H+ to
preserve K+ and Na+). Correct with IV NS + KCl. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.17', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'General Topics', 'The first step in management of severe hyperkalemia (K+ 7.2 mmol/L) with ECG changes is:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'IV calcium gluconate is the FIRST step — it stabilizes the cardiac membrane and protects against
arrhythmias (does NOT lower K+ levels). Then insulin+dextrose to shift K+ intracellularly.
Calcium resonium/dialysis to actually remove K+ from body. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.3', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'General Topics', 'Which IV fluid is most physiological and preferred for resuscitation?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Ringer''s lactate has electrolyte composition closest to plasma. It avoids hyperchloremic acidosis
seen with NS. Preferred for surgical resuscitation. Avoid in hyperkalemia (contains 5 mmol/L K+).
📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.3', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'General Topics', 'Rapid correction of hyponatremia can cause:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Central pontine myelinolysis (osmotic demyelination syndrome) occurs when chronic hyponatremia
is corrected too rapidly (>8-10 mmol/L in 24h). Causes quadriplegia, pseudobulbar palsy.
Slow correction is essential. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.17', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'General Topics', 'Normal saline (0.9% NaCl) has a pH around 5.5 and can cause which acid-base disturbance with large volume infusion?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'NS has supraphysiological chloride (154 mmol/L vs plasma 100). Large volumes cause hyperchloremic
normal anion gap metabolic acidosis. This is why Ringer''s lactate is preferred for large-volume
resuscitation. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.3', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'General Topics', 'A trauma patient has HR 130, BP 80/60, RR 35, confused, urine output 5 mL/hr. What class of hemorrhagic shock is this?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Class III (30-40% blood loss): HR >120, hypotension, RR >30, confused, decreased urine output.
This is the first class to show frank hypotension and requires crystalloid + blood transfusion.
📚 ATLS 10th Ed', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'General Topics', 'Which type of shock presents with hypotension and bradycardia?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Neurogenic shock (spinal cord injury above T6) causes loss of sympathetic tone → vasodilation
+ hypotension + BRADYCARDIA (loss of cardiac sympathetic innervation). All other shock types
have compensatory tachycardia. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.2', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'General Topics', 'The lethal triad in trauma consists of:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'The lethal/vicious triad (hypothermia + acidosis + coagulopathy) creates a death spiral in trauma.
Addressed by damage control surgery and resuscitation. Each component worsens the others.
📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.2', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'General Topics', 'The first-line vasopressor for septic shock is:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Noradrenaline (norepinephrine) is the first-line vasopressor in septic shock per Surviving
Sepsis Campaign guidelines. It is a potent alpha-1 agonist causing vasoconstriction.
Vasopressin is second-line adjunct. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.4', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'General Topics', 'In massive transfusion protocol, the recommended ratio of pRBC:FFP:Platelets is:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'The 1:1:1 ratio (pRBC:FFP:Platelets) mimics whole blood and reduces dilutional coagulopathy.
This is based on the PROPPR trial. Early balanced resuscitation improves survival in massive
hemorrhage. 📚 ATLS 10th Ed; Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.4', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'General Topics', 'The antibiotic of choice for treatment of tetanus is:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Metronidazole is preferred over penicillin for tetanus because penicillin is a GABA antagonist
which can theoretically worsen spasms. Metronidazole kills C. tetani effectively without this risk.
📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.5', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'General Topics', 'A diabetic patient develops rapidly spreading erythema of the perineum with crepitus and severe sepsis. The diagnosis is:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Fournier''s gangrene is necrotizing fasciitis of the perineum and genitalia. Common in diabetics.
It is a surgical emergency requiring aggressive debridement, broad-spectrum antibiotics, and
often multiple return trips to theatre. Mortality is 20-40%. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.5', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'General Topics', 'The optimal timing for prophylactic antibiotic administration in surgery is:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Antibiotics should be given within 60 minutes before incision to achieve adequate tissue levels
at the time of potential contamination. Giving after incision or too early reduces efficacy.
📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.11', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'General Topics', 'Gas gangrene is most commonly caused by:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'C. perfringens produces alpha-toxin (lecithinase/phospholipase C) which destroys cell membranes.
Gas in tissues on X-ray is characteristic. Treatment: Radical surgical debridement + IV penicillin
+ hyperbaric oxygen. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.5', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'General Topics', 'A clean surgical wound (e.g., thyroidectomy) has an expected SSI rate of:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Clean wounds have the lowest SSI rate (1-2%). Clean-contaminated: 5-10%. Contaminated: 10-20%.
Dirty: 20-40%. Wound classification is the most important predictor of SSI.
📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.11', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'General Topics', 'Which is the most important cell in wound healing?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Macrophages are the most important cells — they orchestrate the entire healing process by
phagocytosis, secreting growth factors (PDGF, TGF-β, FGF, VEGF), and recruiting fibroblasts.
Wound healing is impaired in macrophage depletion but NOT in neutrophil depletion. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.6', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'General Topics', 'A scar that extends beyond the original wound margins and does not regress is called:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Keloid extends beyond wound boundaries, does not regress, and has high recurrence after excision.
Hypertrophic scar stays within wound margins and may regress spontaneously.
📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.26', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'General Topics', 'Which vitamin deficiency causes impaired collagen cross-linking leading to scurvy?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Vitamin C (ascorbic acid) is essential for hydroxylation of proline and lysine residues in
collagen. Deficiency causes scurvy with impaired wound healing, bleeding gums, and easy bruising.
📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.26', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'General Topics', 'During wound healing, Type III collagen is replaced by Type I collagen during which phase?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'During remodeling (3 weeks to 1 year), Type III collagen (initial, weaker) is replaced by
Type I collagen (mature, stronger) with increased cross-linking, giving the wound 80% of
original tensile strength. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.6', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'General Topics', 'Which vitamin reverses steroid-induced impairment of wound healing?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Vitamin A reverses the anti-inflammatory and healing-impairment effects of steroids.
It promotes inflammatory phase and collagen synthesis. Steroids inhibit all phases of
wound healing, especially inflammation. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.6', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Hepatobiliary', 'A 45-year-old obese female presents with RUQ pain for 8 hours, fever, and positive Murphy''s sign. USG shows thickened GB wall with pericholecystic fluid. What is the best management?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Current evidence supports early laparoscopic cholecystectomy (<72h) for acute cholecystitis.
It reduces total hospital stay and morbidity without increasing complications compared to delayed
surgery. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.67', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Hepatobiliary', 'Which type of gallstone is most commonly associated with hemolytic anemia?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Black pigment stones (calcium bilirubinate) form due to excess unconjugated bilirubin in hemolytic
anemias (sickle cell, thalassemia, spherocytosis). Brown pigment stones are associated with biliary
infection and stasis. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.55', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Hepatobiliary', 'Reynold''s pentad consists of Charcot''s triad plus:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Reynold''s pentad = Charcot''s triad (fever + jaundice + RUQ pain) + hypotension + altered mental status.
Indicates acute suppurative cholangitis requiring emergency biliary decompression. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.67', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Hepatobiliary', 'During laparoscopic cholecystectomy, what must be achieved before clipping any structure?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Strasberg''s Critical View of Safety requires: hepatocystic triangle cleared of fat/fibrous tissue,
lower 1/3 of GB separated from liver bed, only two structures seen entering GB (cystic duct and artery).
This prevents bile duct injuries. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.55', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Hepatobiliary', 'A patient with gallstones presents with obstructive jaundice. MRCP shows a stone impacted in Hartmann''s pouch compressing the common hepatic duct. What is the diagnosis?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Mirizzi syndrome occurs when a stone impacted in Hartmann''s pouch or cystic duct externally
compresses the CHD causing obstructive jaundice. Type I is external compression; Types II-IV
involve cholecystocholedochal fistula of increasing size. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.67', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Hepatobiliary', 'A 55-year-old cirrhotic patient has a 4 cm liver mass showing arterial enhancement and portal venous washout on CT. AFP is 500 ng/mL. What is the diagnosis?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'In a cirrhotic liver, a mass with arterial enhancement and portal venous washout on triphasic CT
is diagnostic of HCC (LIRADS 5). AFP >400 further supports the diagnosis. No biopsy is needed.
📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.54', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Hepatobiliary', 'Milan criteria for liver transplantation in HCC include:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Milan criteria: single tumour ≤5cm OR up to 3 tumours each ≤3cm, no macrovascular invasion,
no extrahepatic disease. Meeting Milan criteria gives ~75% 4-year survival after transplant.
📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.54', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Hepatobiliary', 'Which variant of HCC occurs in young patients without cirrhosis and has a better prognosis?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Fibrolamellar HCC occurs in young adults (20-40), without cirrhosis or hepatitis. AFP is usually
normal. It shows a central fibrous scar on imaging. Better prognosis because it is often resectable.
📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.54', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Hepatobiliary', 'What is the recommended screening strategy for HCC in high-risk patients?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Surveillance with USG + AFP every 6 months is recommended for high-risk patients (cirrhosis,
chronic HBV, chronic HCV). This detects HCC at an early, potentially curable stage.
📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.66', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Hepatobiliary', 'Aflatoxin B1 exposure causes HCC through mutation of which gene?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Aflatoxin B1 (from Aspergillus flavus contaminating stored grains/nuts) causes a specific
G→T transversion at codon 249 of the p53 tumour suppressor gene, leading to HCC.
📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.54', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Hernia', 'A 60-year-old male has a groin swelling that is NOT controlled by pressure over the deep inguinal ring. The swelling is medial to the inferior epigastric vessels. What type of hernia is this?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Direct inguinal hernia passes through Hesselbach''s triangle, medial to the inferior epigastric
vessels. It is NOT controlled by pressure over the deep ring (unlike indirect hernia which passes
through the deep ring). 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.60', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Hernia', 'Which hernia has the highest risk of strangulation?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Femoral hernia has the highest strangulation risk due to its narrow, rigid neck formed by
the lacunar ligament medially and Cooper''s ligament posteriorly. Emergency surgery is indicated
for all femoral hernias due to this risk. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.60', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Hernia', 'In Richter''s hernia, which part of the bowel wall is involved?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Richter''s hernia involves only the antimesenteric border of the bowel. This is significant because
it can strangulate and even perforate without causing intestinal obstruction (lumen remains patent).
Most commonly occurs in femoral hernias. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.44', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Hernia', 'The gold standard open repair for inguinal hernia is:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Lichtenstein tension-free mesh repair is the gold standard with recurrence rate <1%.
Shouldice is the best tissue (non-mesh) repair. Bassini is historical. Modern practice
favors mesh-based repairs. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.44', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Hernia', 'Which laparoscopic approach for inguinal hernia repair does NOT enter the peritoneal cavity?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'TEP (Totally Extraperitoneal) approach works in the preperitoneal space without entering
the peritoneal cavity. TAPP (Transabdominal Preperitoneal) enters the peritoneum and then
accesses the preperitoneal space. TEP is generally preferred. 📚 Maingot''s, 12th Ed, Part I', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Pancreas', 'Which biochemical marker is most specific for acute pancreatitis?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Serum lipase is more specific for pancreatitis than amylase (amylase can be elevated in
salivary gland disease, bowel obstruction, etc.). Lipase also stays elevated longer (7-14 days
vs 3-5 days for amylase). 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.56', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Pancreas', 'A patient with acute pancreatitis has a CT showing 50% pancreatic necrosis. The patient is afebrile and improving. What is the appropriate management?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Sterile pancreatic necrosis is managed conservatively regardless of extent. Surgery is only
indicated for INFECTED necrosis (suspected by clinical deterioration, gas bubbles on CT,
confirmed by FNA). The step-up approach is used. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.69', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Pancreas', 'Cullen''s sign in acute pancreatitis indicates:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Cullen''s sign = periumbilical bluish discoloration. Grey Turner''s sign = flank ecchymosis.
Both indicate retroperitoneal hemorrhage tracking along tissue planes in severe hemorrhagic
pancreatitis. They are associated with poor prognosis. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.69', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Pancreas', 'Which of the following is NOT a Ranson''s criteria at admission?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Calcium <8 mg/dL is a Ranson''s criterion at 48 hours (C HOBBS), not at admission.
At admission criteria (GA LAW): Glucose >200, Age >55, LDH >350, AST >250, WBC >16,000.
📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.56', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Pancreas', 'A pancreatic pseudocyst is best differentiated from a true cyst by:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'A pseudocyst lacks an epithelial lining — it is encapsulated by fibrous/granulation tissue.
True cysts (serous/mucinous cystadenoma) have an epithelial lining. This distinction is
crucial as mucinous cysts have malignant potential. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.56', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Small Intestine', 'A 22-year-old male presents with periumbilical pain that migrated to the right iliac fossa over 12 hours, associated with anorexia and low-grade fever. What is the most likely diagnosis?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'The classic presentation of acute appendicitis includes periumbilical pain migrating to RIF
(Murphy''s sequence: Pain → Anorexia → Nausea/Vomiting). Mesenteric lymphadenitis can mimic
but usually follows a viral URTI. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.72', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Small Intestine', 'Which investigation is the gold standard for diagnosing acute appendicitis in adults?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'CT abdomen has sensitivity of 94% and specificity of 95% for acute appendicitis. USG is
operator-dependent and preferred in children/pregnant women. MRI is used in pregnancy.
📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.50', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Small Intestine', 'A 30-year-old male presents with RIF pain for 5 days. Examination reveals a palpable, tender mass in RIF. Temperature is 38°C. What is the most appropriate initial management?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'An appendicular mass (not abscess) is managed conservatively with the Ochsner-Sherren regimen:
IV antibiotics, nil by mouth, regular monitoring. Interval appendicectomy at 6-8 weeks.
If abscess forms, percutaneous drainage is indicated. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.72', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Small Intestine', 'What is the most common position of the appendix?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Retrocaecal is the most common position (74%), followed by pelvic (21%). Retrocaecal appendicitis
may present atypically with flank pain and positive Psoas sign. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.72', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Small Intestine', 'A carcinoid tumour of 1.5 cm is found at the tip of the appendix during appendicectomy. What is the appropriate management?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Carcinoid tumour <2 cm at the tip of the appendix: appendicectomy alone is sufficient.
Right hemicolectomy is indicated when tumour is >2 cm, at the base, has lymph node involvement,
or shows mesoappendicular invasion. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.50', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Small Intestine', 'A patient with cirrhosis and ascites develops fever and abdominal pain. Ascitic fluid shows PMN count of 400/mm³. What is the most appropriate treatment?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'This is spontaneous bacterial peritonitis (SBP) — PMN >250/mm³ in ascitic fluid. Treatment is
medical with IV 3rd-generation cephalosporin (cefotaxime/ceftriaxone). Surgery is NOT indicated
in primary/spontaneous peritonitis. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.46', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Small Intestine', 'What is the most common cause of pneumoperitoneum?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Perforated DU (anterior wall) is the MC cause of pneumoperitoneum. Gas under the diaphragm
on erect CXR is seen in ~80% of perforations. Perforated appendicitis rarely causes
pneumoperitoneum. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.61', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Small Intestine', 'Mannheim Peritonitis Index score >26 is associated with mortality greater than:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'MPI >26 predicts mortality >50%. Factors increasing score include age >50, organ failure,
malignancy, duration >24h, diffuse peritonitis, and fecal exudate. It is a useful prognostic
tool for secondary peritonitis. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.46', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Small Intestine', 'A 40-year-old presents with sudden epigastric pain, board-like rigidity, and absent bowel sounds. Erect X-ray shows bilateral air under the diaphragm. The immediate next step is:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Pneumoperitoneum with peritonitis = perforated hollow viscus (most likely DU). After brief
resuscitation, emergency laparotomy (or laparoscopy) for Graham''s omental patch repair is
indicated. No further investigations needed. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.61', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Small Intestine', 'The organism most commonly causing SBP in adults is:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'E. coli is the MC organism in adult SBP (via bacterial translocation from gut). In children,
Strep. pneumoniae is MC. SBP is monomicrobial; polymicrobial infection suggests secondary
peritonitis (perforation). 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.46', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Stomach Duodenum', 'A gastric cancer specimen shows signet ring cells with diffuse thickening of the stomach wall. This is characteristic of:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Linitis plastica (leather bottle stomach) is the diffuse type (Lauren classification) with
signet ring cells, diffuse mural infiltration, and poor prognosis. It corresponds to Borrmann
Type IV. It is associated with blood group A and peritoneal spread (Krukenberg tumour). 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.48', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Stomach Duodenum', 'Virchow''s node is located in the:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Virchow''s node (Troisier''s sign) is an enlarged left supraclavicular lymph node, typically
from gastric cancer metastasis via the thoracic duct. Irish''s node = left axillary.
Sister Mary Joseph = periumbilical. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.64', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Stomach Duodenum', 'What is the standard lymphadenectomy for curative gastric cancer surgery?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'D2 lymphadenectomy (perigastric nodes + nodes along celiac trunk branches) is the
standard for curative intent. At least 16 nodes should be harvested for adequate staging.
D1 alone has higher recurrence. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.48', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Stomach Duodenum', 'Krukenberg tumour is a metastasis to the:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Krukenberg tumour = bilateral ovarian metastasis, classically from gastric cancer (diffuse/signet ring type)
via transcoelomic spread. Characterized by mucin-secreting signet ring cells. Also seen from
colon and breast primary. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.64', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Stomach Duodenum', 'The sequential pathway of gastric carcinogenesis (Correa cascade) starts with:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Correa cascade: H. pylori infection → chronic superficial gastritis → atrophic gastritis →
intestinal metaplasia → dysplasia → invasive carcinoma. This applies to the intestinal type
of gastric cancer. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.48', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Stomach Duodenum', 'A patient presents with sudden-onset severe epigastric pain and board-like rigidity. Erect X-ray shows air under the diaphragm. What is the most likely diagnosis?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Pneumoperitoneum (air under diaphragm) with sudden epigastric pain and board-like rigidity
is classic for hollow viscus perforation. DU perforation (anterior wall) is the most common cause.
📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.63', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Stomach Duodenum', 'Which type of vagotomy does not require a drainage procedure?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'HSV (parietal cell vagotomy) preserves the nerve of Latarjet and antral innervation,
maintaining pyloric function. Hence no drainage procedure is needed. It has the lowest
dumping/diarrhea rates but highest recurrence. 📚 Maingot''s, 12th Ed, Part IV', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Stomach Duodenum', 'A patient with chronic DU presents with projectile non-bilious vomiting and succussion splash. ABG shows metabolic alkalosis. What is the diagnosis?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'GOO from chronic DU causes pyloric stenosis → projectile non-bilious vomiting, visible
gastric peristalsis, succussion splash. Loss of HCl → hypochloremic hypokalemic metabolic
alkalosis with paradoxical aciduria. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.48', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Stomach Duodenum', 'Which gastric ulcer type is associated with high acid secretion and behaves like a duodenal ulcer?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Johnson Type II (body + duodenal ulcer) and Type III (prepyloric) are associated with
high acid secretion. Types I and IV are low-acid types. Type V is NSAID-related.
📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.48', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Stomach Duodenum', 'Passaro''s triangle, where gastrinomas are most commonly located, is bounded by:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Passaro''s triangle (gastrinoma triangle) is bounded by the junction of cystic and common
bile duct superiorly, junction of D2 and D3 inferiorly, and junction of neck and body of
pancreas medially. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.48', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Trauma', 'The most commonly injured organ in blunt abdominal trauma is:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'The spleen is the MC injured organ in blunt abdominal trauma due to its subcapsular location
and friable parenchyma. Liver is 2nd MC. Most splenic injuries in hemodynamically stable
patients can be managed non-operatively. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.18', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Trauma', 'A trauma patient is hypotensive with absent breath sounds and hyperresonance on the left chest. Trachea is deviated to the right. What is the immediate management?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'This is tension pneumothorax — a clinical diagnosis. Do NOT wait for X-ray. Immediate needle
decompression at 2nd intercostal space, midclavicular line, followed by chest tube insertion
(5th ICS, anterior axillary line). 📚 ATLS 10th Ed', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Trauma', 'In the FAST exam, which view is the most sensitive for detecting free fluid?', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Morrison''s pouch (hepatorenal space) is the most dependent area in a supine patient and is
the most sensitive view for detecting free intraperitoneal fluid. It should be examined first.
📚 ATLS 10th Ed', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Trauma', 'Contraindication for urinary catheterization in trauma includes:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Blood at meatus, high-riding prostate on DRE, and perineal/scrotal bruising suggest urethral
injury. Urethral catheterization is contraindicated — perform retrograde urethrogram first.
If injury confirmed, suprapubic catheter is placed. 📚 ATLS 10th Ed', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Trauma', 'The principle of damage control surgery involves all EXCEPT:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Damage control surgery specifically avoids definitive repair in the first operation. The unstable
patient gets abbreviated surgery (stop bleeding, control contamination), ICU resuscitation to
correct the lethal triad, then planned re-exploration for definitive repair. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.27', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Vascular', 'A patient with varicose veins has a positive Perthes test (varicosities don''t empty and become more painful on walking with tourniquet). This indicates:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Perthes test assesses deep vein patency. If varicosities become MORE prominent and painful with
tourniquet + exercise, deep veins are occluded. Surgery on superficial veins is CONTRAINDICATED
as they are the only venous drainage pathway. 📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.57', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Vascular', 'The most common inherited thrombophilia predisposing to DVT is:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Factor V Leiden (activated protein C resistance) is the MC inherited thrombophilia, present in
5% of Caucasians. It causes a 5-fold increased risk of DVT (heterozygous) and 50-fold (homozygous).
📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.64', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Vascular', 'An ABPI of 0.4 in a patient with rest pain indicates:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'ABPI <0.5 with rest pain indicates critical limb ischemia (Fontaine stage III-IV).
Revascularization is urgent to prevent limb loss. Normal ABPI >0.9, claudication 0.5-0.9.
📚 Bailey & Love, 28th Ed, Ch.56', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Vascular', 'The gold standard investigation for diagnosing DVT is:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Duplex USG (compression ultrasonography) is the gold standard for DVT diagnosis — non-invasive,
readily available, high sensitivity for proximal DVT. Non-compressibility of vein is diagnostic.
D-dimer is used to exclude DVT in low-probability patients. 📚 Sabiston, 21st Ed, Ch.64', 2, 'nucleux-content', '{}'),
  ('Surgery', 'Vascular', 'The single most important intervention in management of peripheral arterial disease is:', '[{"key": "A", "text": "a"}, {"key": "B", "text": "b"}, {"key": "C", "text": "c"}, {"key": "D", "text": "d"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Smoking cessation is the most important modifiable risk factor in PAD. It reduces progression,
improves claudication distance, reduces cardiovascular events, and improves graft patency.
